Dr. Avul Pakir Jainulabdeen Abdul Kalam, also known as APJ Abdul Kalam, was an Indian scientist and politician who served as the President of India from 2002 to 2007. He was born on October 15, 1931 in the Indian state of Tamil Nadu and received a degree in physics from St. Joseph's College in 1954. He then pursued further studies in aerospace engineering at the Madras Institute of Technology, earning his degree in 1957.
After completing his studies, Kalam joined the Indian Space Research Organisation (ISRO) as a scientist, where he played a key role in developing India's first satellite launch vehicle. In 1969, he moved to the Defense Research and Development Organization (DRDO), where he worked on the development of missiles. In the 1980s, he became the Chief Scientific Adviser to the Prime Minister of India and the Secretary of the Defense Research and Development Organization (DRDO).
In 2002, Kalam was elected as the President of India, becoming the country's eleventh president and the first scientist to hold the position. He was known for his strong commitment to education, science, and technology, and was often referred to as the "People's President" for his accessibility and humble demeanor. During his tenure as President, he focused on improving the country's education system and promoting science and technology.
Kalam passed away on July 27, 2015 at the age of 83. He is remembered as a great leader and a visionary who inspired millions of people around the world with his dedication to science and education.

